crossValidate <- function(dataset, id, dependentVariable, indVariables) {
  allPredictions <- data.frame()
  cvID_list <- unique(dataset[[id]])
    for (i in cvID_list) {
      thisFold <- i
      cat("This hold out fold is", thisFold, "\n")
      fold.train <- filter(dataset, dataset[[id]] != thisFold) %>% as.data.frame() %>% 
        dplyr::select(id, geometry, indVariables, dependentVariable)
      fold.test  <- filter(dataset, dataset[[id]] == thisFold) %>% as.data.frame() %>% 
        dplyr::select(id, geometry, indVariables, dependentVariable)
      regression <-
        glm(assaultsCount ~ ., family = "poisson", 
            data = fold.train %>% 
              dplyr::select(-geometry, -id))
      thisPrediction <- 
        mutate(fold.test, Prediction = predict(regression, fold.test, type = "response"))
      allPredictions <-
        rbind(allPredictions, thisPrediction)
      }
  return(st_sf(allPredictions))
}

mapTheme <- function(base_size = 10, title_size = 10) {
  theme(
    text = element_text(family = 'font', color = "black"),
    plot.title = element_text(family = 'font', size = title_size,colour = "black"),
    plot.subtitle=element_text(family = 'font', face="italic"),
    plot.caption=element_text(family = 'font', hjust=0),
    axis.ticks = element_blank(),
    panel.background = element_blank(),axis.title = element_blank(),
    axis.text = element_blank(),
    axis.title.x = element_blank(),
    axis.title.y = element_blank(),
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
    panel.border = element_rect(colour = "black", fill=NA, size=.7),
    strip.text.x = element_text(family = 'font', size = 9))
}

1 Introduction

In this project, I intend to build a model to predict assault occurrences in Chicago. The assumption behind this model is that crime risk is a function of exposure to a series of risk factors. The model explores the relationship between exposure and crime occurrence, hoping to generalize the experience to other space-time.

This type of predictive policing has its problems and is under heated debate. Police crime data-sets are not comprehensive records of all crimes that have occurred, but are very likely to suffer from selection bias against some communities, i.e., the crimes happening in some places are more likely to be recorded. The generalizability of such a model is compromised, because the mechanism behind the selection bias is not taken into account. Furthermore, the prediction outputs of such a model will also be biased against certain communities, resulting in increased surveillance and more reported crimes, and in turn, more predicted crimes, in these communities.

While keeping these critiques in mind, risk modelling is often proved effective for crime prediction, especially compared to traditional models based on kernel density.

Assault is one of the most common crimes recorded in Chicago. Figure 1. shows the distribution of assaults that took place in 2018 and their hot spots. The assault occurrences are highly spatially clustered around a few urban cores. Selection bias may be an issue, if this clustering is partly due to the fact that assaults are more likely to be recorded in city centers.

#-----Getting assault data for Chicago in 2018-----
allCrimes2018 = read.socrata("https://data.cityofchicago.org/resource/3i3m-jwuy.json") %>%
  filter(., (!is.na(x_coordinate)) & (!is.na(y_coordinate))) %>%

assaults2018 = allCrimes2018 %>% filter(., primary_type == 'ASSAULT') %>%

Figure 1.

In the following sections of this document, I build and iteratively improve a model to predict assault cases in Chicago based on data from 2018, until it attains reasonable accuracy and generalizability. Then, I test the model against assault observations in the next year (2019), while comparing it with the traditional kernel density method. Finally, I initiate a discussion on whether I would recommend this algorithm to be put into production.

2 Data & feature engineering

2.1 The fishnet

To facilitate modelling, a grid (fishnet) of 1500*1500-feet cells are created, and the grid cell would be the basic modelling unit. Figure 2. maps the assaults by grid cell.

#-----Fishnet-----
fishnet = st_make_grid(chicagoBoundary, cellsize = 1500) %>% # Cell size 1500ft
  .[chicagoBoundary] %>%
  st_sf() %>%
  mutate(uniqueID = rownames(.))

#-----Count assaults in fishnet-----
fishnet_1 = 
  dplyr::select(assaults2018) %>%
  mutate(assaultsCount = 1) %>%
  aggregate(., fishnet, sum) %>%
  mutate(assaultsCount = replace_na(assaultsCount, 0),
         cellID = rownames(.))

#---Plot assaults by grid cell-----
ggplot(data = fishnet_1) +
  geom_sf(aes(fill = assaultsCount), color = NA) +
  scale_fill_gradient(low = color1, high = color2,
                      breaks = c(0, 91),
                      labels = c(0, 91), name = 'Count')+
  labs(title = 'Count of assaults by fishnet, 2018') +
  mapTheme()

Figure 2.

2.2 The risk factors

Next, I download and wrangle a set of risk factor features into the fishnet. Seven features are downloaded from the Chicago 311 reports of abandoned vehicles, street lights out, alley lights out, vacant buildings, sanitation complaints, potholes, and graffiti (Figure 3.). It is also reasonable to hypothesize that assaults are more likely to occur where population density and the unemployment rate are higher. Tract-level population density and unemployment rate are calculated from the ACS 5-year estimates of 2018. Another hypothesis is that assaults are spatially converged in the city center; therefore, the distant from each cell to the centroid of Loop (considered the center of Chicago) is calculated.

#-----Get neighborhood----
neighborhoods = 
  st_read("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/blackmad/neighborhoods/master/chicago.geojson") %>%
  st_transform(crs)

#-----Get ACS-----
tract = get_acs(geography = 'tract',
                variables = c('B01001_001E',
                              'B01001A_001E',
                              'B17005_001E',
                              'B17005_005E',
                              'B17005_010E',
                              'B17005_016E',
                              'B17005_021E'),
                year = 2018, state = 17, county = 031, geometry = TRUE,
                output = 'wide') %>%
  st_transform(crs) %>%
  rename(totalPopulation = B01001_001E) %>%
  mutate(area = st_area(.) %>% as.numeric(),
         density = totalPopulation * 1000000 / area,
         pctWhite = B01001A_001E / totalPopulation,
         unemploymentRate = (B17005_001E - B17005_005E - 
           B17005_010E - B17005_016E - B17005_021E) / B17005_001E) %>%
  dplyr::select(-starts_with('B')) %>%
  .[chicagoBoundary,]

#-----Distance to center of loop-----
loopCenter = 
  filter(neighborhoods, name == 'Loop') %>%
  st_centroid()

#-----Join ACS data to fishnet-----
fishnet_2 = 
  st_centroid(fishnet_1) %>%
  st_join(dplyr::select(tract, density, pctWhite, unemploymentRate)) %>%
  st_drop_geometry()%>%
  left_join(fishnet_1) %>%
  st_sf()

#-----Assign neighborhoods-----
fishnet_3 = 
  st_centroid(fishnet_2) %>%
  st_join(dplyr::select(neighborhoods, name)) %>%
  st_drop_geometry()%>%
  left_join(fishnet_2) %>%
  st_sf() %>%
  mutate(neighborhood = name)

#-----Join distance to Loop center-----
fishnet_4 = fishnet_3
fishnet_4$distLoop = st_distance(st_centroid(fishnet_3), loopCenter) %>%
  as.numeric()

The exposure of each cell to any risk factor is calculated by averaging the distances from the cell centroid to its three nearest occurrences of the factor. Figure 4. shows the final engineered features joined to the fishnet.

Figure 4.

Apart from the risk factors, the racial component is also downloaded from the ACS to test the models generalizability across different racial contexts later. Neighborhood boundaries are used for spatial leave-one-group-out cross-validation later. Finally, a unique cvID is created for each cell to facilitate k-fold cross-validation.

fishnet_6 = fishnet_5 %>%
  mutate(cvID = sample(round(nrow(fishnet) / 29), size = nrow(fishnet),
                       replace = TRUE))

3 Spatial processes

Crimes tend to cluster in space. So far, however, each grid cell is considered to be an independent observation with certain exposure to risk factors; the spatial variation of assault occurrences is not fully accounted for. In this step, I perform a Local Morans I test to identify the hot spots of assaults. The results are shown in Figure 5.

fishnet_7 = 
  fishnet_6 %>%
  mutate(assaultsHotspotSig = localmoran(
    fishnet_6$assaultsCount,
    nb2listw(poly2nb(as_Spatial(fishnet_6), queen = TRUE),
             style = 'W',
             zero.policy = TRUE))[,5])
moranTable = 
  cbind(
    as.data.frame(localmoran(
    fishnet_6$assaultsCount,
    nb2listw(poly2nb(as_Spatial(fishnet_6), queen = TRUE),
             style = 'W',
             zero.policy = TRUE))),
    as.data.frame(fishnet_6)
  ) %>%
  st_sf() %>%
  dplyr::select(Assaults_count = assaultsCount,
                Local_Morans_I = Ii,
                P_Value = `Pr(z != E(Ii))`) %>%
  mutate(Significant_hotspots = ifelse(P_Value <= 0.05, 1, 0)) %>%
  gather(Variable, Value, -geometry)

vars = unique(moranTable$Variable)
varList = list()

for(i in vars){
  varList[[i]] = 
    ggplot() + 
    geom_sf(data = filter(moranTable, Variable == i),
            aes(fill = Value), color = NA) +
    scale_fill_gradient(low = color1, high = color2, name = '') +
    labs(title = i) +
    mapTheme() + theme(legend.position = 'bottom')
}

do.call(grid.arrange, c(varList, ncol = 4))

Figure 5.

To incorporate the spatial processes into the model, I will add the results of the Local Morans test as independent variables. Using the 0.01 significance threshold, I generate a dummy variable denoting whether a cell belongs to a local significant cluster. I also measure the nearest distance from each cell centroid to the nearest significant cluster.

fishnet_8 = fishnet_7 %>%
  mutate(assaultsHotspotSig.01 = 
           ifelse(assaultsHotspotSig <= 0.01, 1, 0)) %>%
  mutate(sigDist = 
           nn_function(st_coordinates(st_centroid(fishnet_7)),
                       st_coordinates(st_centroid(
                         filter(fishnet_7, assaultsHotspotSig.01 == 1)
                       )), 1)) %>%
  na.omit()

  labs(title = 'Poisson distribution')+
  plotTheme2()

grid.arrange(ncol = 2, assaultsDistribution, poissonDistribution)

Figure 7.

Two cross-validation methods are used. The first, K-fold validation, divides the data into k (in this case, 100) folds, each of which takes turns to be the test set, and the model trained on the rest of the data is tested on this fold. The second method is the spatial leave-one-group-out (LOGO) cross-validation, which assumes a neighborhood can take advantage of the experiences of other neighborhoods. Each time, the train set leaves one neighborhood out, and then the model is tested for its generalizability on the remaining neighborhood.

The first model takes in all the features described above. Two cross-validation methods are used.

regVars1 = c('abandonedVehiclesDist',
             'vacantBuildingsDist',
             'alleyLightsOutDist',
             'streetLightsOutDist',
             'sanitationComplaintsDist',
             'graffitiDist',
             'potHolesDist',
             'distLoop',
             'assaultsHotspotSig.01',
             'sigDist')
## K-fold CV
reg1KFoldCV = crossValidate(
  dataset = fishnet_8,
  id = 'cvID',

                observation = assaultsCount,
                prediction = Prediction,
                geometry)%>%
  mutate(., error = prediction - observation)

## Spatial LOGO CV
reg1SpatialCV = crossValidate(
  dataset = fishnet_8,
  id = 'name',
  dependentVariable = 'assaultsCount',
  indVariables = regVars1
) %>%
  dplyr::select(fold = name,
                observation = assaultsCount,
                prediction = Prediction,
                geometry)%>%
  mutate(., error = prediction - observation)

## K-fold cross-validation
error1KFoldCV = 
  reg1KFoldCV %>%
  group_by(fold) %>%
  summarize(meanObs = mean(observation, na.rm = TRUE),
            meanError = mean(error, na.rm = TRUE),
            meanAbsError = mean(abs(error), na.rm = TRUE),
            sdMeanAbsError = sd(abs(error), na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  st_drop_geometry() %>%
  as.data.frame()

# Spatial LOGO cross-validation
error1SpatialCV = 
  reg1SpatialCV %>%
  group_by(fold) %>%
  summarize(meanObs = mean(observation, na.rm = TRUE),
            meanError = mean(error, na.rm = TRUE),
            meanAbsError = mean(abs(error), na.rm = TRUE),
            sdMeanAbsError = sd(abs(error), na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  st_drop_geometry() %>%
  as.data.frame() %>%
  left_join(dplyr::select(neighborhoods, name, geometry),
            by = c('fold' = 'name')) %>%
  st_sf()

The mapping of prediction errors reveal major underestimations in some parts of Chicago, e.g.the urban cores. Figure 9. shows that the random k-fold cross-validation produces more accurate results than the spatial LOGO cross-validation. This means that there is strong spatial variation between neighborhoods; the experience of some neighborhoods may not be well generalized into other neighborhoods, especially those where assaults are more frequent.

This could mean either a flaw in the prediction model, or reflects a selection bias of assault reports, because assaults may be more likely to be reported in urban cores. I will come back to the issue at the end of this document.

5 Accounting for high outliers

In the last section, although I have added the hot spots of assaults into the model, it still fails to account for very high assault occurrences in some parts of Chicago, especially in the urban cores.

In this section, I intend to improve prediction accuracy by accounting for these high outliers. The improved models divides the fishnet into quintiles based on the frequency of assaults and add this as an independent variable.

6.2 Across time

As a final step, I use the model from 2018 to test on assault records in 2019, testing its generalizability across time. In doing so, I compare this model with the traditional method based on kernel density. Based on assault predictions in 2018, I use the kernel density model and this risk prediction model to divide Chicago into five risk categories. By overlaying the risk category map with the observed assaults in 2019, it is evident that the risk prediction model is more accurate in predicting assaults (Figure 17.).

#-----Download crime 2019-----
allCrimes2019 = read.socrata("https://data.cityofchicago.org/resource/w98m-zvie.json") %>%
  filter(., (!is.na(x_coordinate)) & (!is.na(y_coordinate))) %>%
  st_as_sf(coords = c('x_coordinate', 'y_coordinate'), crs = crs, agr = 'constant') %>%
  distinct() %>% #Unit is feet
  dplyr::select(primary_type, description)

assaults2019 = allCrimes2019 %>% filter(., primary_type == 'ASSAULT') %>%
  dplyr::select(-primary_type, -description) %>%
  mutate(type = 'Assault')
#-----Use kernel density to predict-----

assaultsPPP = as.ppp(st_coordinates(assaults2018), W = st_bbox(fishnet_10))
assaultsKD = density.ppp(assaultsPPP, 3000)

#-----Compare prediction with observation-----
assaultsKDE = as.data.frame(assaultsKD) %>%
  st_as_sf(coords = c('x', 'y'), crs = crs) %>%
  aggregate(., fishnet_10, mean) %>%
  mutate(label = 'Kernel Density',
         riskCategory = ntile(value, 5)) %>%
  cbind(
    aggregate(
      dplyr::select(assaults2019) %>% mutate(assaultsCount2019 = 1),., sum) %>%
      mutate(assaultsCount2019 = replace_na(assaultsCount2019, 0))
  ) %>%
  dplyr::select(label, riskCategory, assaultsCount2019)

#-----Use risk prediction to predict-----

assaultsRisk = reg3SpatialCV %>%
  mutate(label = 'Risk Predictions',
         riskCategory = ntile(prediction, 5)) %>%
  cbind(
    aggregate(
      dplyr::select(assaults2019) %>% mutate(assaultsCount2019 = 1),., sum) %>%
      mutate(assaultsCount2019 = replace_na(assaultsCount2019, 0))
    ) %>%
  dplyr::select(label, riskCategory, assaultsCount2019)
kernelDensityPlot = ggplot(data = assaultsKDE)+

Figure 18. plots the ratio of observed assaults in 2019 happening in the five risk-category areas as defined by the kernel density model and the risk prediction model. The risk prediction model as developed in this document seems to have an advantage by successfully forecasting more assaults in its high-risk zones. Therefore, the risk prediction model here may be better than the traditional kernel-density method.

rbind(assaultsKDE, assaultsRisk) %>%
  st_set_geometry(NULL) %>% na.omit() %>%

7 Closing remarks

In this project, I have developed a risk-prediction model to forecast crimes (assaults) in Chicago. By iteratively improving the model, I have been able to predict assaults more accurately than the traditional hot-spot method, especially in terms of accounting for very high assault occurrences in Chicagos urban cores. This suggests that the risk-prediction method, or predictive policing, is a powerful planning tool.

Nevertheless, I would hesitate to recommend my algorithm to be put into production. As mentioned earlier, the records of assaults are likely to suffer from selection bias, in which assaults are more likely to be recorded in central urban areas. Should this be the case, then it would explain the intense convergence of assaults in central area. In this scenario, my model would only be able to predict assault records rather than actual assault risks, and it would lead probably lead to unfair outcomes such as broken windows policing. The selection bias of assaults should be more closely examined.
